Bibliography proposed by Chor Pharn:

Essential References
Charles S. Maier, The Project-State and Its Rivals (2023) — on the rise and collapse of mass mobilisation as the organising principle of modernity.

Anton Jäger, “The Rise and Fall of the Project State,” American Affairs (2023) — clarifies how project societies dissolved into neoliberal fragmentation.

Stanisław Lem, Summa Technologiae (1964) — distinction between instrumental and existential technologies.

Benjamin Bratton, The Stack (2016) — foundational account of planetary computation and sovereignty.

Jan Kulveit, “The Memetics of AI Successionism” (2025) — on the psychological consequences of being displaced by non-human learning.

Thomas Meaney, “The Future of Magazines… and the World,” The Nation (2025) — defines America’s “carnival of recognition” and China’s state-backed science.

Chor Pharn, “Wordless Places, Worldless Places” (2024) — introduces AI as existential tool and the idea of Kosmos Law.

Alex Hochuli, George Hoare & Philip Cunliffe, The End of the End of History (2021) — on the populist backlash and the exhaustion of Western progress narratives.

Reiner Kümmel, The Second Law of Economics (2011) — energy as the true basis of growth and legitimacy.

